00:07:03,920 --> 00:07:07,800
Talk about what is a utility curve, how you think use that to build better products.

100
00:07:07,800 --> 00:07:12,880
This is pretty easy cuz it's a very familiar S-curve where, you know, you have uh it's flat,

101
00:07:12,880 --> 00:07:17,040
it starts arcing up, and then there's a really steep part, and then it levels off again.

102
00:07:17,040 --> 00:07:25,080
And on the horizontal axis, uh you can think of cost or effort.

103
00:07:25,080 --> 00:07:29,080
And on the vertical axis, it's value or convenience.

104
00:07:29,080 --> 00:07:31,600
It kind of depends exactly what you're talking about.

105
00:07:31,600 --> 00:07:38,760
But the idea is um the first bit of effort you put into something doesn't result in a huge amount of value,

106
00:07:38,760 --> 00:07:42,600
and then there's some magic threshold where it produces an enormous amount of value,

107
00:07:42,600 --> 00:07:45,240
and then continued investment doesn't really pay off.

108
00:07:45,240 --> 00:07:49,840
The most basic example I can think of is let's say you're making a hammer.

109
00:07:49,840 --> 00:07:52,960
And on that bottom axis, it's now quality.

110
00:07:52,960 --> 00:07:58,320
And if the hammer uh has a handle that breaks with any impact, then it's totally useless.

111
00:07:58,320 --> 00:08:00,680
And if you make it a little bit stronger, it's still pretty useless.

112
00:08:00,680 --> 00:08:05,080
And it's kind of like junk junk junk junk junk, okay, good, great.

113
00:08:05,080 --> 00:08:06,640
Then it doesn't matter anymore.

114
00:08:06,640 --> 00:08:12,880
If you're making an app, okay, this app's going to have users, and so let's make a users table in a database,

115
00:08:12,880 --> 00:08:15,680
and so far you have generated no value.

116
00:08:15,680 --> 00:08:22,520
The reason I I felt like this was so important is because we would talk about like a feature.

117
00:08:22,520 --> 00:08:25,400
Um and usually features are thought of as as binary.

118
00:08:25,400 --> 00:08:28,440
Like you you either have this feature or you don't.

119
00:08:28,440 --> 00:08:39,320
And so, the argument I guess was, have we just not invested enough in this, or have we got all the value or convenience or,

120
00:08:39,320 --> 00:08:41,960
